Then whenever an Edge is added to Gaffer, 2 Entities should also be added, one at the source vertex and one at the destination vertex. Aggregation will then merge the entities together. These entities could be added as part of a generator, however that would mean any edges that are added not via a generator would not get the relevant cardinalities. Alternatively we could create an AbstractAddElementHandler that wrapped the Iterable<Elements> in a TransformOneToManyIterable and for each edge it lazily adds 2 cardinality entities.

For example in the AbstractAddElementsHandler we could have something like this (however it would mean calling instanceof, Collections.singleton and Arrays.asList a lot - there must be a more efficient way of doing it):

```java
return new TransformOneToManyIterable<Element, Element>(elements) {
    @Override
    protected Iterable<Element> transform(final Element element) {
        if(element instanceof Entity) {
            return Collections.singleton(element);
        }
        final Edge edge = (Edge) element;
        return Arrays.asList(
                edge,
                createCardinaltity(edge.getSource(), edge), 
                createCardinaltity(edge.getDestination(), edge)
        );
    }
};


private Entity createCardinaltity(final Object vertex, final Edge edge) {
        final Entity entity = new Entity("Cardinality", vertex);
        entity.putProperty("edgeGroup", edge.getGroup());

        // create a hyperLogLogPlus instance using the provided edge.
        entity.putProperty("cardinality", hyperLogLogPlus);

        // add any optional required properties

        return entity;
    }
```

