When querying a graph it is often useful to be able to see a summary of the number of groups an operation would return.

For example:

If you execute a GetRelatedElements operation with seed "vertex1" it could return:

``` json
Edge {"source": "vertex1", "destination": "vertex2", "directed": true, "group": "groupA"}
Edge {"source": "vertex1", "destination": "vertex3", "directed": true, "group": "groupA"}
Edge {"source": "vertex3", "destination": "vertex4", "directed": true, "group": "groupA"}
Edge {"source": "vertex4", "destination": "vertex5", "directed": true, "group": "groupB"}
Entity {"vertex": "vertex1", "group": "groupA"}
Entity {"vertex": "vertex1", "group": "groupB"}
```

If you execute an OperationChain of GetRelatedElements followed by CountGroups it could return:

``` json
entityGroups: {"groupA": 1, "groupB": 1}
edgeGroups: {"groupA": 3, "groupB": 1}
```

The CountGroups operation consist of:
input: Iterable<? Extends Element>
output: GroupCounts

Where GroupCounts looks a bit like:

``` java
// Map of entity group to count
Map<String, Integer> entityGroups;

// Map of edge group to count
Map<String, Integer> edgeGroups;
```

This operation should have a default handler in the Store class.

Like the Accumulo store implementation. most store implementations will probably return an iterable that needs to be closed. Currently if users fully iterate over the results then the Accumulo results iterable will be automatically closed. However, if only a few results are read then it is too easy to forget to manually close the iterable as users have to do something like:

``` java
if(results instanceof CloseableIterable) {
    ((CloseableIterable)results).close();
}
```

This also couples client code directly to the Accumulo implementation and requires knowledge of how Accumulo handles operations. 

Note - implementing this change will require modifications to a large number of classes.

